GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 2
SENATE BILL 205
Second Edition Engrossed 4/8/25
Short Title: Clarify Swimming Pool Laws/Priv. Pool Rentals. (Public)
Sponsors: Senator Jarvis (Primary Sponsor).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 3, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT PROHIBITING LOCAL BOARDS OF HEALTH FROM REGULATING PRIVATE
3 POOLS SERVING SINGLE FAMILY DWELLINGS; CLARIFYING THE SCOPE OF
4 SWIMMING POOL LAWS BY AMENDING THE EXEMPTION FOR PRIVATE POOLS
5 SERVING SINGLE FAMILY DWELLINGS; AND MAKING OTHER TECHNICAL
6 CHANGES TO G.S. 130A-280.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1. G.S. 130A-39(b) reads as rewritten:
9 "(b) A local board of health may adopt a more stringent rule in an area regulated by the
10 Commission for Public Health or the Environmental Management Commission where, in the
11 opinion of the local board of health, a more stringent rule is required to protect the public health;
12 otherwise, the rules of the Commission for Public Health or the rules of the Environmental
13 Management Commission shall prevail over local board of health rules. However, a local board
14 of health may not adopt a rule concerning a private pool serving a single family dwelling
15 otherwise exempt from regulation pursuant to G.S. 130A-280 or a rule concerning the grading,
16 operating, and permitting of food and lodging facilities as listed in Part 6 of Article 8 of this
17 Chapter and as defined in G.S. 130A-247(1), and a local board of health may adopt rules
18 concerning wastewater collection, treatment and disposal systems which are not designed to
19 discharge effluent to the land surface or surface waters only in accordance with
20 G.S. 130A-335(c)."
21 SECTION 2. G.S. 130A-280, as amended by Section 4.51 of S.L. 2024-49, reads as
22 rewritten:
23 "§ 130A-280. Scope.Scope and definitions.
24 (a) This Article Part provides for the regulation of public swimming pools in the State as
25 they may affect the public health and safety. As used in this Article, the term "public swimming
26 pool" means any structure, chamber, or tank containing an artificial body of water used by the
27 public for swimming, diving, wading, recreation, or therapy, together with buildings,
28 appurtenances, and equipment used in connection with the body of water, regardless of whether
29 a fee is charged for its use. The term includes municipal, school, hotel, motel, apartment,
30 boarding house, athletic club, or other membership facility pools and spas, spas operating for
31 display at temporary events, and artificial swimming lagoons. As used in this Article, an
32 "artificial swimming lagoon" means any body of water used for recreational purposes with more
33 than 20,000 square feet of surface area, an artificial liner, and a method of disinfectant that results
34 in a disinfectant residual in the swimming zone that is protective of the public health. This Article
35 Part does not apply to any of the following:
*S205-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) A private pool serving a single family dwelling and used only by the residents
2 of the dwelling and their guests.guests, regardless of whether their guests gain
3 use of the private pool through a sharing economy platform or pay a fee for
4 its use. In all cases in which a fee is exchanged for access to a private pool
5 serving a single family dwelling that is used only by the residents of the
6 dwelling and their guests, the private pool shall be maintained in good and
7 safe working order.
8 (2) A private pool serving a single family dwelling meeting the minimum
9 requirements of this subdivision which is offered to, and used by, individuals
10 on a temporary basis utilizing a sharing economy platform. For the purposes
11 of this subdivision, a sharing economy platform means an online platform
12 used to facilitate peer-to-peer transactions to acquire, provide, or share access
13 to goods and services. For the purposes of this subdivision, a pool must meet
14 all of the following minimum requirements:
15 a. Pools must have proper fencing and barriers to prevent unsupervised
16 access, especially by children. The fence should be at least 4 feet high
17 with a self-latching gate.
18 b. Pools must have clear and conspicuous signage posted around the pool
19 area specifying pool rules, depth markers, and any potential hazards.
20 c. Pools must be equipped with basic lifesaving equipment, including life
21 rings and reaching poles.
22 d. Pool decks and surrounding areas must have non-slip surfaces.
23 e. Pools must have properly fitted covers for all submerged suction
24 outlets.
25 f. Pools must be well-maintained with proper chemical balance and
26 cleanliness to ensure safe and healthy swimming conditions.
27 (3) Therapeutic pools used in physical therapy programs operated by medical
28 facilities licensed by the Department or operated by a licensed physical
29 therapist, nor to therapeutic chambers drained, cleaned, and refilled after each
30 individual use.
31 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this Part:
32 (1) Artificial swimming lagoon. – Any body of water used for recreational
33 purposes with more than 20,000 square feet of surface area, an artificial liner,
34 and a method of disinfectant that results in a disinfectant residual in the
35 swimming zone that is protective of the public health.
36 (2) Public swimming pool. – Any structure, chamber, or tank containing an
37 artificial body of water used by the public for swimming, diving, wading,
38 recreation, or therapy, together with buildings, appurtenances, and equipment
39 used in connection with the body of water, regardless of whether a fee is
40 charged for its use. The term includes municipal, school, hotel, motel,
41 apartment, boarding house, athletic club, or other membership facility pools
42 and spas, spas operating for display at temporary events, and artificial
43 swimming lagoons.
44 (3) Sharing economy platform. – An online platform used to facilitate
45 peer-to-peer transactions to acquire, provide, or share access to goods and
46 services."
47 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025.
